---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Plain Theory Labs — certification framework for sustainable AI compute infrastructure";
---

<BaseLayout title="Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>Plain Theory Labs</h1>
    <p class="thesis">
      Plain Theory Labs is a research and engineering lab building the certification framework for
      sustainable AI compute infrastructure. We build engines that take real operational data from
      GPU clusters and data centers and produce traceable, assumption-explicit efficiency grades
      that institutions can use for policy decisions, procurement requirements, and public
      reporting.
    </p>

    <p>
      We are researchers, engineers, and systems scientists with careers inside HPC. We have
      worked at research universities, national labs, and academic medical centers. We have
      watched monitoring data accumulate without any framework to act on it. We are building
      that framework.
    </p>

    <p>
      The problem is structural. AI compute is scaling faster than anyone can measure its impact,
      and the tools that exist today tell operators what is happening but not what to do about it.
      There is no independent methodology for grading compute sustainability, no standard that an
      HPC director, a sustainability office, or a government agency can reference when making
      decisions about infrastructure. We are building that standard.
    </p>

    <p>
      Our first engine is ACE. Future engines will address workload scheduling, cooling
      efficiency, real-time carbon intensity, and hardware procurement. Together they form a
      certification framework for AI compute infrastructure — grounded in telemetry, explicit in
      its assumptions, designed to produce grades an institution can stand behind publicly, before
      government regulation imposes a standard that no one helped design.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Why now</h2>

    <p>
      Communities near data centers are pushing back on water usage, power draw, and grid strain.
      The EU AI Act includes environmental impact provisions. Federal AI infrastructure spending
      is under growing scrutiny. Institutions that want to get ahead of this need a methodology
      and an independent grade. Neither exists yet.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>ACE</h2>

    <p>
      ACE is our first engine. It ingests Slurm scheduler exports and GPU telemetry, scores
      per-job efficiency, applies a conservative safety overlay that blocks anything it cannot
      defend, and produces a single-file HTML report with traceable recommendations and fully
      disclosed assumptions.
    </p>

    <p>
      We validated ACE on the MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset: 35,745 real jobs, scheduler logs,
      and DCGM telemetry. Average GPU utilization was 25.7%, median utilization 16%, 41% of jobs
      ran under one minute, and 33% showed near-zero GPU activity. These are not projections.
      They are what the engine found in a published, peer-reviewed dataset from a production HPC
      system.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/ace">ACE Engine &rarr;</a>
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <p class="inline-links"><a href="/contact">Work with us &rarr;</a></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
